Introduction

The current document provides additional results from the analysis of temporal trends in treatment patterns of SLE patients in Sweden described in Poster P150 at SLEuro2024.

The study population is identified from the Swedish National Patient Register (NPR) including all unique individuals with â‰¥2 visits listing an International Classification of Diseases (ICD) code for SLE in the NPR (M32, excluding drug-induced lupus M32.0), including at least one visit with a specialist (clinics/departments which typically diagnose SLE; rheumatology, dermatology, nephrology, internal medicine, and pediatrics). Incident cases are identified by restricting the population to patients with their first visit listing the ICD code for SLE between 2005-07-01 and 2021-09-01, allowing at least 4.5 years to exclude prevalent cases. The current study is restricted to patients with time between first visit listing the ICD code for SLE and confirmation of SLE diagnosis within 1 year to mkae sure cohorts defined by year of diagnosis are comparable.

Analyses of temporal trends of HCQ and GC use are adjusted for age, sex, educational level, country of birth, hospital (university/other) for SLE diagnosis, number of hospitalizations and number of out-patient visits during the preceding year. Age is standardized to 50 years.
